subject_prompt_600:
Office Open XML files contain a hierarchical tree structure. The first object in a folder tree is called root. A folder in the tree can be nested. Each subfolder inside the root can be its own object, which means you can write an entire spreadsheet within one folder. Each nested folder is called subfolder. Each parent subfolder must be a fully-qualified Office Open XML file name (the same as the parent folder). The XML file name must include a '.' and not have any spaces in it.

The XML file type includes a 'type' property which specifies what kind of file that is (such as Microsoft.xls or Open Office.ods). This property also contains optional attributes. These are specified after the file's name in quotation marks. The following table lists these attributes. You can only define them if the file is also a folder.

Name Required / Optional Attribute Type Description Author Unknown or no No The person who signed the XML file Author ID Unknown No Unique identifier that appears in the XML file Author Date Unknown No The date when the XML file was written to by the file author (in ISO 8601 time) Date_Written Unknown No The current date and time when the XML file was created; this attribute does not apply to Word documents AutoCAD AutoCAD - - XML tags are handled in the way described above; see the XSLT Format Documentation for details. Bases Base - - Specifies the base object used for the entire document for drawing and layout. Use this parameter for the XML file format. Credentials Authorization credentials - - Unknown. Used by MS-PACX and other Microsoft Office applications. Customization Customization - - Customized XML tag. Dictionaries Dictionary - - List of dictionaries used by OLE extensions. Default Dictionary - - Default dictionary used to build the XML document. Elements Element - - The root node of the XML file element hierarchy. Entries Element - - An enumerated value of the XML file content. Errors Object Error - - Unrecognized element. Grouping Grouping - - Indicates that the document contains a sequence of elements. In the example file, the grouping indicates that the document contains three elements - two text nodes and one image node. Hierarchy Hierarchy - - Describes the order of presentation in the XML file. Language Language - - Specifies the language in which the file is interpreted. The language must be an ISO 639 code.
